Philippine Stocks: Anchor, Cebu Air, Filinvest, Metro Pacific

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-07-08T04:28:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-08/ayala-cebu-air-filinvest-vista-philippines-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.4 percent to
4,391.46, completing a 0.9 percent gain this week. The measure
posted its third weekly gain.  Anchor Land Holdings Inc. (ALHI)  , a builder of
apartments, climbed 2.6 percent to 19.50 pesos, the highest
level since the stock began trading in August 2007. The property
developer declared a 100 percent stock dividend and said
shareholders approved a plan to boost capital with the sale of
preferred shares, a regulatory filing showed.  Cebu Air Inc. (CEB)  , the largest Philippine budget
carrier, decreased 1.9 percent to 85.40 pesos, the lowest level
since June 15. The airline expects profit to decline this year
due to higher  oil prices , President Lance Gokongwei said.  Filinvest Development Corp. (FDC)  , which has investments
in sugar and property, climbed 1.8 percent to 5.13 pesos, the
highest level since May 5. The company said it will lead a group
that plans to construct a 300-megawatt power plant in the
province of Misamis Oriental for $450 million.  Metro Pacific Investments Corp. (MPI)  , which has
investments in toll roads, water and hospitals, sank 5 percent
to 3.60 pesos, the sharpest loss since Nov. 11. The company said
it completed the sale of 2.4 billion shares at 3.60 pesos each.
Metro Pacific closed at 3.79 pesos yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
